    riskFactors: ["Structural PALM causes: endometrial or cervical Polyps (prevalence increases with age), Adenomyosis (multiparity, prior uterine surgery), Leiomyomas (African American ethnicity, obesity, nulliparity), Malignancy/hyperplasia (age over 45, obesity, chronic anovulation, tamoxifen)","Non-structural COEIN causes: Coagulopathy (von Willebrand disease affects 1% of population, present in up to 13% of women with HMB)","Ovulatory dysfunction from PCOS, thyroid disorders, hyperprolactinemia, hypothalamic amenorrhea (stress, weight loss, exercise)","Endometrial causes: primary disorders of endometrial hemostasis, deficiency of local vasoconstrictors (endothelin-1, PGF2-alpha)","Iatrogenic causes: anticoagulant therapy, hormonal contraceptives, copper IUD, tamoxifen, corticosteroids","Obesity (BMI greater than 30) promoting estrogen excess through peripheral aromatization of androgens","Reproductive age extremes: adolescent HPO axis immaturity and perimenopause with declining ovarian follicular reserve"],
    diagnostics: ["Systematic evaluation using PALM-COEIN framework: assess for structural causes first (PALM) using imaging, then non-structural causes (COEIN) using laboratory evaluation","Transvaginal ultrasound as initial imaging: evaluates endometrial thickness (greater than 4 mm postmenopausal is abnormal), identifies fibroids (submucosal vs intramural vs subserosal), polyps, adenomyosis signs (heterogeneous myometrium, asymmetric wall thickening)","Saline infusion sonohysterography (SIS) to distinguish endometrial polyps from submucosal fibroids and evaluate the endometrial cavity","Laboratory workup: CBC with ferritin, beta-hCG, TSH, prolactin, coagulation screen (PT, aPTT, vWF antigen, ristocetin cofactor activity, factor VIII)","Endometrial biopsy via Pipelle sampling for histologic evaluation of endometrial hyperplasia or malignancy (indicated for age greater than 45, or younger with risk factors)","MRI pelvis for detailed characterization of adenomyosis, mapping of fibroid number/size/location pre-surgically, and evaluating suspected malignancy","Hysteroscopy with directed biopsy as gold standard for evaluating and treating intracavitary pathology (polyps, submucosal fibroids)"],
    management: ["Classify AUB etiology using PALM-COEIN before initiating treatment: structural causes may require procedural intervention; non-structural causes are typically managed medically","For AUB-O (ovulatory dysfunction): combined hormonal contraceptives for cycle regulation, or cyclic progestin therapy; address underlying cause (levothyroxine for hypothyroidism, metformin for PCOS)","For AUB-L (leiomyomas): LNG-IUD for submucosal fibroids less than 3 cm, GnRH agonists preoperatively to reduce size and correct anemia, hysteroscopic myomectomy for submucosal fibroids, uterine artery embolization for multiple symptomatic fibroids","For AUB-P (polyps): hysteroscopic polypectomy with histologic examination to exclude malignancy","For AUB-C (coagulopathy): hematology referral, desmopressin (DDAVP) for mild von Willebrand disease, antifibrinolytics (tranexamic acid), hormonal management to reduce menstrual flow","For AUB-M (malignancy/hyperplasia): refer to gynecologic oncology; endometrial hyperplasia without atypia may be managed with progestin therapy and surveillance; atypia requires hysterectomy or close progestin therapy with repeat biopsy if fertility desired","Iron replacement therapy for all patients with iron-deficiency anemia: oral ferrous sulfate or IV iron (ferric carboxymaltose) for severe anemia or oral intolerance"],
    nursingActions: ["Obtain comprehensive menstrual and bleeding history: age at menarche, cycle regularity, flow duration and volume (PBAC score), intermenstrual and postcoital bleeding, associated dysmenorrhea, impact on daily activities","Assess for bleeding diathesis: family history of bleeding disorders, easy bruising, epistaxis, gingival bleeding, postpartum hemorrhage history, surgical bleeding history (suggestive of coagulopathy)","Prepare patients for diagnostic procedures: NPO for hysteroscopy, full bladder for transabdominal ultrasound, timing of endometrial biopsy (secretory phase preferred for dating, any time for cancer screening)","Educate patients on the PALM-COEIN classification: explain that AUB has multiple possible causes that may coexist, and that systematic evaluation identifies the specific cause to guide targeted treatment","Monitor treatment response: menstrual diary or PBAC scoring, serial hemoglobin and ferritin levels, patient-reported quality of life outcomes","Coordinate pre-surgical optimization: correct anemia with IV iron before elective surgery, administer GnRH agonists 2 to 3 months preoperatively if prescribed to reduce fibroid size","Screen for endometrial cancer risk factors at annual well-woman visits: obesity, chronic anovulation, PCOS, tamoxifen use, family history of Lynch syndrome"],
